

Generators:
> A generator is a special function in JavaScript that can pause and resume execution.
> 


ex:
  function* numbers() {
  yield 1;
  yield 2;
  yield 3;
}

const gen = numbers();

console.log(gen.next().value); // 1
console.log(gen.next().value); // 2
console.log(gen.next().value); // 3

function* → creates a generator
yield → pauses the function
.next() → resumes execution
Generator does not run fully at once


Decorators:
> A decorator is a function that wraps another function to add extra behavior.
> A decorator is a function that modifies or enhances another function, method, or class without changing its original code.
>
  Decorators are not part of standard JavaScript yet.
  They are commonly used in TypeScript and Babel (experimental).

> Decorators are functions that enhance classes or methods by wrapping them with additional behavior without modifying their original implementation.

EX:
  function log(fn) {
  return function () {
    console.log("Function is called");
    return fn();
  };
}

function sayHello() {
  console.log("Hello");
}

const decoratedHello = log(sayHello);
decoratedHello();

OUTPUT:-
--------------------->
Function is called
Hello

log wraps sayHello
Adds extra logic before calling the original function
Original function is unchanged
  
